{"parse":{"title":"beef","pageid":45015,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|en|:inh|enm:bef}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|bef|beef, bef, beof}}, borrowed from {{der|en|xno|beof}}, {{der|en|fro|buef}}, {{m|fro|boef||ox}} (modern {{m+|fr|bœuf}}); from {{der|en|la|bōs|bovem|ox}}, from {{der|en|itc-pro|*gʷōs}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʷṓws}}. {{doublet|en|cow}}.\n\nBeef in the sense of “a grudge, argument” was originally an American slang expression:<ref>{{cite-web|year=2016–2019|title=Origin of the Slang AmE and BrE Usage of “Beef”|titleurl=https://english.stackexchange.com/questions/336475/origin-of-the-slang-ame-and-bre-usage-of-beef|work=StackExchange}}.</ref>\n* attested as a verb “to complain” in 1888: “He'll beef an' kick like a steer an' let on he won't never wear 'em.”— ''New York World'', 13 May;\n* attested as a noun “complaint, protest, grievance, sim.” in 1899: “He made a Horrible Beef because he couldn't get Loaf Sugar for his Coffee.”—''Fables in Slang'' (1900) by George Ade, page 80.\n\nAs to the possible origin of this American usage, it has been suggested that it can be traced back to a British expression for “alarm”, first recorded in 1725:<ref>''The New Canting Dictionary: Comprehending All the Terms, Ancient and Modern, Used in the Several Tribes of Gypsies, Beggars, Shoplifters, Highwaymen, Foot-pads'' etc. London.</ref>  \"BEEF 'to alarm, as ''To cry beef  upon us''; they have discover'd us, and are in Pursuit of us\". The term \"beef\" in this context would be a Cockney rhyming slang of {{m|en|thief}}. However, the continuous use of a similar expression, including its assumed semantic shift to 'complaint' in the United States from the 1880s onwards, needs further clarification.<ref>{{R:World Wide Words|entry=Beefing|url=qa/qa-bee2}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈbiːf/|/ˈbɪi̯f/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-beef.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{rhymes|en|iːf|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|beef}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~|*|s|beeves}}\n\n[[File:Choice.png|thumb|A [[chunk]] of beef ''({{senseno|en|Q192628}})'']]\n# {{senseid|en|Q192628}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[meat]] from [[cattle]] or other [[bovine]]s; especially, that from adults.\n#: {{syn|en|cowflesh|oxflesh}}\n#: {{hyper|en|meat<id:Q10990>|<|food<id:Q2095>|<|substance<id:stuff>|material#Noun|stuff#Noun}}\n#: {{hypo|en|veal<id:Q957434><qq:often construed as coordinate>}}\n#: {{cot|en|<!--cardinal cot-->pork<id:Q191768>|mutton<id:Q14566073>|lamb<id:Q643419>|poultry<id:Q178559>|chicken<id:Q864693>}}\n#: {{ux|en|I love eating '''beef'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en| He was cooking '''beef''' for lunch.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Red Jordan Arobateau|title=Leader of the Pack|page=136|pageurl=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=nFi8AVCa0wsC&pg=PA136&dq=%22roast+beefs%22&hl=en&ei=_Wd9TbmcNIiecL_f7bkG&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=12&ved=0CHgQ6AEwCw#v=onepage&q=%22roast%20beefs%22&f=false|passage=But the cars & trucks held cartons of roast chickens, slabs of cheeses, loaves of bread, racks of hotdogs, case upon case of soft drinks, cases of bottled sparkling water, pies, cakes, roast '''beefs''' & baked hams.}}\n## {{lb|en|in the meat industry|on|_|product packaging}} The [[edible]] portions of a [[cow]] (including those which are not [[meat]]).\n##: {{co|en|[[lean finely textured beef|lean finely textured '''beef''']]}}\n##: {{co|en|[[boneless lean beef trimmings|boneless lean '''beef''' trimmings]]}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|author=Jordan Valinsky|title=McDonald’s is finally selling the Chicken Big Mac in the US|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2024/10/03/food/mcdonalds-chicken-big-mac|date=2024-10-03|passage=McDonald’s has been vocal about adding more chicken to its menu, which is generally cheaper than '''beef'''. CEO Chris Kempczinski said in its most recent earnings call that it’s focused on adding “growth drivers like chicken” in an attempt to reverse slumping sales. Chicken is now on par with '''beef''' sales at its restaurants, he added.}}\n## {{lb|en|by extension|slang|uncountable}} [[muscle|Muscle]] or [[musculature]]; [[size]], [[strength]] or [[potency]].\n##: {{ux|en|Put some '''beef''' into it! We've got to get the car over the bump.}}\n##: {{ux|en|We've got to get some '''beef''' into the enforcement provisions of that law.}}\n## {{lb|en|figurative|slang|uncountable}} [[essence|Essence]], [[content]]; the important part of a document or project.\n##: {{syn|en|meat}}\n##: {{ux|en|The '''beef''' of his paper was a long rant about government.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[bovine|Bovine]] animals.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Who's the real McCoy? Abilene's Joseph in 8 Wonders contest|work=Abilene Recorder Chronicle|date=October 21, 2010|passage=However, there were millions of head of '''beef''' roaming the plains of Texas.}}\n# {{lb|en|now|chiefly|North American|countable|now|uncommon|plural ''beeves''}} A [[bovine]] ([[cow]] or [[bull]]) being raised for its [[meat]].\n#: {{ux|en|Do you want to raise '''beeves'''?}}\n#* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=VIII|chapter=Of Scythian beasts, and those that are bred in the North parts|year=1601|pages=199–200|pageref=199|passage=Howbeit, that country bringeth forth certain kinds of goodly great wild '''bœufes''': to wit, the Biſontes, mained with a collar, like Lions: and the Vri, a mightie ſtrong beaſt, and a ſwift: which the ignorant people call Buffles, whereas indeed the Buffle is bred in Affrica, and carieth ſome reſemblance of a calfe rather, or a ſtag.}}\n#* {{RQ:Cowper Homer|volume=I|book=XV|page=394|lines=398–401|passage=As when two lions in the ſtill dark night / An herd of '''beeves''' ſcatter or num'rous flock / Suddenly, in the abſence of the guard, / So fled the heartleſs Greeks, {{...}}}}\n#* '''1903''' March, Henry Mason Baum, Frederick Bennett Wright, George Frederick Wright, ''Records of the Past'', volume II, part III, page 87, translating the laws of Hammurabi:\n#*: 263. If he [one to whom a '''beef''' or sheep is loaned] ruins the '''beef''' or sheep that was loaned him, he is to return to the owner a '''beef''' for a '''beef''' and a sheep for a sheep.\n#* '''1920–1930''', [https://statemuseum.nd.gov/database/photobook/index.php?content=photobook-itemdetails&ID=PH_I_149437&CollectionNmbr=00250&PBID=89024 Photo in the North Dakota State Museum]:\n#*: Cutting out a '''Beef''' for branding\n#* {{quote-web |en |year=2012 |quotee=Bart Reilly |title=Beef |url=https://ontariodialects.chass.utoronto.ca/search?word_id=10 |work=Ontario Dialects Project |location=Toronto |publisher=University of Toronto |accessdate=July 5, 2022 |text=I remember I killed a '''beef''' one time by myself. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705190632/https://ontariodialects.chass.utoronto.ca/search?word_id=10 |archivedate=5 July 2022 }}\n# {{lb|en|slang|uncountable|or|countable|plural ''beefs''}} A [[grudge]]; dislike (of something or someone); lack of faith or trust (in something or someone); a reason for a dislike or grudge. (often + ''[[with]]'')\n#: {{ux|en|He's got '''beef''' over what you said.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He's got a '''beef''' with everyone in the room.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Remember what happened last fall? That's his '''beef''' with me.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1997|title={{w|Going Back to Cali (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Going Back to Cali}}|artist=w:The Notorious B.I.G.|album=Life After Death|passage=All I got is '''beef''' with those that violate me / I shall annihilate thee}}\n# {{lb|en|prison slang}} A criminal [[charge]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=15 Feb 86|volume=7|journal=Gay Commmunity News|number=29|url=https://repository.library.northeastern.edu/downloads/neu:m046hh67x|page=8|title=untitled|author=Ed Mead|text=I'm in prison for attempting to kill two police officers (a genuine bum '''beef''') and am alleged to be a part of a group of mad bombers.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=15 Feb 86|volume=7|journal=Gay Commmunity News|number=29|url=https://repository.library.northeastern.edu/downloads/neu:m046hh67x|page=9|title=untitled|author=Ed Mead|text=The man most recently murdered is said to have been a key defense witness in the trial of two other Indians facing hanging '''beefs''' for their alleged killing of a guard.}}\n# {{lb|en|Dorset}} [[fibrous|Fibrous]] [[calcite]] or [[limestone]], especially when occurring in a jagged layer between [[shale]]s in [[Dorset]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1895|author=Geological Survey of Great Britain|title=The Jurassic Rocks of Britain: Pub. by Order of the Lords Commissioners of Her Majesty's Treasury|page=243\n|text=Clays, shales, sands, red and green marls, and alum shale, with occasional layers of \"'''beef'''\" (fibrous carbonate of lime) {{...}} Chief \"'''Beef'''\" Beds, Dark (alum) shales with \"'''beef'''\" and selenite, beds of limestone, and layers of perished shells. ''Cyrena'' and Cyrides.<br/>Corbula Beds. Layers of shelly limestone, shale, alum shale, and marl, with \"'''beef'''\" and selenite.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993|author=Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society|title=Proceedings - Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society|volume=114-115|page=190\n|text=Medium-grey paper shales with '''beef'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2007-05-10|author=Robin McInnes; Jenny Jakeways; Helen Fairbank; Emma Mathie|title=Landslides and Climate Change: Challenges and Solutions: Proceedings of the International Conference on Landslides and Climate Change, Ventnor, Isle of Wight, UK, 21-24 May 2007|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781000006704|page=421\n|text={{...}} beds of limestone and thin layers of &apos;'''beef'''&apos; (fibrous calcite){{nb...}}}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nA [[calf]] is a bovine, so, technically, the flesh of a calf, used for food, is beef. However, it is not common to use this term for the flesh of a calf; instead, it is referred to with the more specific term {{m|en|veal}}.\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|Albany beef|beef measles\n|baby beef\n|baron of beef\n|beefalo\n|beefaroni\n|beef bayonet\n|beef bourguignon\n|beef-brained\n|beefburger\n|beefcake\n|beef chit\n|beef curtains\n|beefeater\n|Beefeater\n|beefer\n|beef flaps\n|beefhead\n|beefheaded\n|beefheart\n|beef house,beefhouse,beef-house\n|beef injection\n|beefish\n|beef jerky\n|beefless\n|beeflike\n|beef mami\n|Beefmaster\n|beef olive\n|beef on the hoof\n|beef on weck\n|beef plate\n|beef rib\n|beefsteak\n|beef stew\n|beef tea\n|beef tomato\n|beef to the hoof\n|beef trust\n|beef Wellington\n|beef-witted\n|beefy\n|big as bull-beef\n|boneless lean beef trimmings\n|bully beef\n|carabeef\n|chipped beef\n|corned beef\n|cry beef\n|grass beef\n|ground beef\n|ham and beef shop\n|hot beef injection\n|hot-beef injection\n|hung beef\n|I don't eat beef\n|Italian beef\n|kippered beef\n|Kobe beef\n|lean finely textured beef\n|mess beef\n|Mongolian beef\n|neckbeef\n|park the beef bus in tuna town\n|pit beef\n|reef and beef\n|roast beef\n|roast beef curtains\n|roast-beef plant\n|round of beef\n|salt beef\n|smoked beef\n|squash the beef\n|ugly as bull-beef\n|what's the beef\n|where's the beef\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|bovine}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|haw|pipi|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mi|pīwhi|bor=1}}\n* {{desctree|pt|bife|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|es|bife|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|meat}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|beesvleis}}\n* Ahom: {{t|aho|𑜃𑜢𑜤𑜰𑜫 𑜑𑜥}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|mish lope}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|бозуныҥ эди}}, {{t|alt|уйдыҥ эди}}\n* Apache:\n*: Western Apache: {{t|apw|magashi bitsiʼ}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|لَحْم بَقَر|m}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|տավարի միս}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|behiki}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|я́лавічына|f}}\n* Bourbonnais-Berrichon: {{t|roa-bbn|bœû|m}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|bevin}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|гове́ждо|n}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|အမဲသား}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|vedella|f}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᏩᎦ ᎭᏫᏯ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|牛肉}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|牛肉|tr=gû-bah}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|牛肉}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|bewin|m}}, {{t|kw|kig bewin|m}}, {{t|kw|kig bowin|m}}\n* Corsican: {{t+|co|boie}}, {{t+|co|boiu}}, {{t+|co|boi}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|hovězí|n}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|oksekød|n}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|bief}}, {{qualifier|beefsteak}} {{t+|nl|biefstuk}}, {{t+|nl|rundvlees|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|bovaĵo}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|veiseliha}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|neytakjøt|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|naudanliha}}, {{qualifier|meat from a bull}} {{t+|fi|häränliha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|bœuf|m}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{t|fy|kowefleis|n}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ძროხის}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Rindfleisch|n}}, {{t+|de|Ochsenfleisch}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|βοδινό|n}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|nersussuup neqaa}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|ગોમાંસ}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|([[בְּשַׂר]]) [[בָּקָר]]|m|tr=(b'sar) bakár}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|गोमांस}}, {{t+|hi|गोश्त|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|marhahús}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|nautakjöt|n}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|bovokarno}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|daging sapi}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|mairteoil|f}}\n* Isan: {{t-needed|tts}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|manzo|m}}, {{t|it|carne bovina|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|牛肉|tr=ぎゅうにく, gyūniku}}, {{t+|ja|ビーフ|tr=bīfu}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|сиыр еті}}\n* Khakas: {{t|kjh|інек иді}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|សាច់គោ|tr=sac koo}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|쇠고기}}, {{t+|ko|소고기}}, {{qualifier|in compounds}} {{t|ko|-우(牛)}}, {{qualifier|uncommon}} {{t|ko|우육(牛肉)}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t|ky|уй эти}}\n* Lao: {{t+|lo|ຊີ້ນງົວ}}, {{t|lo|ເນຶ້ອງົວ}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|būbula|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|liellopa gaļa|f}}, {{t|lv|vērša gaļa|f}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|jautiena|f}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|Rëndfleesch|n}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|говедско|n}}, {{t|mk|телешко|n}}, {{t|mk|јунешко|n}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|daging lembu}}, {{qualifier|informal use}} {{t+|ms|daging}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|ċanga|f}}\n* Manx: {{t|gv|feill vart|f}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kiko kau}}, {{t|mi|mīti kau}}, {{t|mi|pīwhi}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|गोमांस}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|bef}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|үхрийн}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|béégashii bitsįʼ}}\n* Nepali: {{t|ne|बीउ}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|viande dé vaque|f}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|storfekjøtt|n}}, {{t|nb|oksekjøtt|n}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|storfekjøt|n}}, {{t|nn|storfekjøtt|n}}, {{t|nn|oksekjøt|n}}, {{t|nn|oksekjøtt|n}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|buòu|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|گوشت گاو|tr=gušt-e gâv}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{t|pdt|Rintfleesch|n}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|wołowina|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|[[carne]] [[de]] [[vaca]]|f}}, {{t|pt|[[carne]] [[bovina]]|f}} {{q|formal}}, {{t+|pt|carne|f}} {{q|Brazil, informal}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|waka aycha}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|vită|f}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|charn-bov|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|говя́дина|f}}, {{t+|ru|теля́тина|f}} {{qualifier|veal}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|vuovssábiergu}}, {{t|se|šibitbiergu}}, {{t|se|oamebiergu}}\n* Samoan: {{t|sm|povi}}, {{t|sm|fāsipovi}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|गोमांस|n}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|mairtfheòil|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|говедина|f}}, {{t|sh|телетина|f}}, {{t|sh|јунетина|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|govedina|f}}, {{t+|sh|teletina|f}}, {{t+|sh|junetina|f}}\n* Shor: {{t|cjs|нек эди|tr=nek edi}}\n* Sindhi: {{t|sd|ٻوڙا}}\n* Sinhalese: {{t|si|හරක් මස්}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|hovädzie|n}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|govedina|f}}, {{t+|sl|teletina|f}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|gowjeze měso|n}}, {{t|dsb|gowjezyna|f}}\n*: Upper Sorbian: {{t|hsb|howjaze mjaso|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|carne de res|f}}, {{t|es|carne de vaca|f}}, {{t|es|[[carne]] [[bovina]]|f}}, {{t|es|rotí|m}} {{q|Dominican Republic}}, {{t|es|matagón|m}} {{q|El Salvador}}\n* Swahili: {{t|sw|[[nyama]] ya [[ng'ombe]]}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|nötkött|n}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|karneng baka}}\n* Telugu: {{t+check|te|గోమాంసము}}, {{t-check|te|ఎద్దు మాంసం}}, {{t-check|te|గేదె మాంసం}}, {{t-check|te|దున్న మాంసం}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|เนื้อวัว|tr=nʉ́ʉa-wuua}}, {{t+|th|เนื้อ}}\n* Tibetan: {{t-needed|bo}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|sığır eti}}, {{qualifier|veal}} {{t+|tr|dana eti}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|я́ловичина|f}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|گوشت}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|كالا گۆشى}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t|vi|[[thịt]] [[bò]]}} ({{t|vi|[[䏦]][[𤙭]]}})\n* Volapük: {{t|vo|bubamit}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|boû|m}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|cig eidion|m}}, {{t+|cy|bîff|m}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t|wyi|bulanga}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|רינדפֿלייש|n}}\n* Zhuang: {{t|za|laeblaz}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|cow, bull|cow|bull}}\n\n{{trans-top|grudge; dislike}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|牢騷}}\n\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|afkeer|m}}, {{t|de|[[heftige]] [[ergernis]]|f}}, \n* German: {{t+|de|Groll|m}}, {{t|de|[[heftige]] [[Verärgerung]]|f}}, {{t+|de|Rochus|m}}, {{t+|de|Widerwillen|m}}, {{t+|de|Beschwerde|f}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kosa|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|animosidad|f}}, {{t+|es|aversión|f}},  {{t+|es|bronca|f}}, {{t+|es|contienda|f}}, {{t+|es|discordia|f}}, {{t+|es|disputa|f}}, {{t+|es|enemistad|f}}, {{t+|es|hostilidad|f}}, {{t+|es|rencor|m}}, {{t+|es|resentimiento|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|beefwood}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|slang}} To [[complain#Verb|complain]].\n#* {{RQ:Wodehouse Jeeves in the Offing|chapter=X|passage=“Don't you like the Red Room?” “The Red Room!” I gathered from his manner that he had not come to '''beef''' about his sleeping accommodation.}}\n#* {{RQ:Noire Thug-A-Licious|page=131|passage=\"Who's Precious?\" she '''beefed''' when she saw the big tattoo running down my inner arm.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To add weight or strength to.\n#: {{syn|en|beef up}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1969|title=Hot Rod|volume=22|page=59\n|passage=First off, the axle housing was '''beefed''' by welding areas where extreme loading is evident (black marked areas).}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|slang}} To [[fart]]; break wind.\n#: {{ux|en|Ugh, who just '''beefed''' in here?}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|chiefly|Yorkshire}} To [[cry]].\n#: {{ux|en|David was '''beefing''' last night after Ruth told him off.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To [[fail]] or [[mess up]].\n#: {{ux|en|I '''beefed''' my presentation hard yesterday.}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|_|AAVE|MLE|MTE|intransitive|slang}} To [[feud]] or hold a [[grudge]] against.\n#: {{ux|en|Those two are '''beefing''' right now — best you stay out of it.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|slang|Australia}} To sing or speak loudly; to cry out.\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|beef up|beef out}}\n<!-- Compared to cow -->\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj|-}}\n\n# Being a [[bovine]] [[animal]] that is being [[raise]]d for its [[meat]].\n#: {{ux|en|We bought three '''beef''' calves this morning.}}\n# [[produce|Producing]] or known for [[raise|raising]] lots of [[#Noun|beef]].\n#: {{co|en|'''beef''' farms}}\n#: {{co|en|'''beef''' country}}\n# [[consist|Consisting]] of or [[contain]]ing [[#Noun|beef]] as an [[ingredient]].\n#: {{co|en|'''beef''' stew}}\n# {{lb|en|slang}} {{cap|beefy}}; [[powerful]]; [[robust]].\n#: {{ux|en|Wow, your audio setup is '''beef'''!}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|beefy}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|being a bovine animal raised for meat}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|producing or raising lots of beef meat}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|having beef as an ingredient}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|гове́жди}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|wołowy|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|говя́жий}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===References===\n<References/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=beef|Feeb|feeb}}\n\n{{C|en|Meats}}\n\n==Afrikaans==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|af|LL-Q14196 (afr)-Oesjaar-beef.wav}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{af-verb|bewende}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|af|bewe}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-beef.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|eːf|s=1}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|nl|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nl|beven||bare-verb}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|bef}}"}}